<span id="vi.iv.xxviii"></span>

<span id="vi.iv.xxviii-p1"></span> <span class="c1"><span
id="vi.iv.xxviii-p1.1"></span>Chapter XXVIII.—Of the Spiritual Victim,
Which Prayer is.</span>

<span id="vi.iv.xxviii-p2"></span>For this is the spiritual victim <span
id="fr_8935"></span>[8936](#fn_8935.md) which has abolished the pristine
sacrifices.  “To what purpose,” saith He, “(bring ye) me the multitude
of your sacrifices? I am full of holocausts of rams, and I desire not
the fat of rams, and the blood of bulls and of goats. For who hath
required these from your hands?” <span
id="fr_8936"></span>[8937](#fn_8936.md) What, then, God *has* required the
Gospel teaches.  “An hour will come,” saith He, “when the true adorers
shall adore the Father in spirit and truth. For God is a Spirit, and
accordingly requires His adorers to be such.” <span
id="fr_8937"></span>[8938](#fn_8937.md) We are the true adorers and the
true priests, <span id="fr_8938"></span>[8939](#fn_8938.md) who, praying in
spirit, <span id="fr_8939"></span>[8940](#fn_8939.md) sacrifice, in spirit,
prayer,—a victim proper and acceptable to God, which assuredly He has
required, which He has looked forward to <span
id="fr_8940"></span>[8941](#fn_8940.md) for Himself! This *victim*, devoted
from the whole heart, fed on faith, tended by truth, entire in
innocence, pure in chastity, garlanded with love, <span
id="fr_8941"></span>[8942](#fn_8941.md) we ought to escort with the
pomp <span id="fr_8942"></span>[8943](#fn_8942.md) of good works, amid
psalms and hymns, unto God’s altar, <span
id="fr_8943"></span>[8944](#fn_8943.md) to obtain for us all things from
God.

